  "executive_summary": {
    "headline": "Absorption rate is remarkably stable across threshold choices (CV=0.077), ranging from 0.118 to 0.151 across the full 5x4 parameter grid. Shuffled-label controls (0.746) exceed measured absorption at ALL 20 threshold combinations, confirming that control failure is structural and threshold-independent. Letter-level rankings are highly preserved (mean Kendall tau=0.977). Magnitude gap has more influence than cosine threshold (effect: 0.0295 vs 0.0104), consistent with JumpReLU's hard activation threshold mechanism.",
    "key_findings": [
      "CV=0.077: absorption rate varies by only 0.033 across 20 threshold combinations",
      "Control failure is universal: shuffled rate (0.746) exceeds measured rate at all 20 cells",
      "Mean Kendall tau=0.977: letter absorption rankings are stable regardless of threshold",
      "Magnitude gap (effect=0.0295) matters more than cosine threshold (effect=0.0104)",
      "Cosine threshold [0.01] is/are saturated -- too loose to discriminate",
      "Probe quality confound: rho(F1, absorption) = -0.762 (p=0.0000)"
    ],
    "paper_implications": [
      "Threshold sensitivity results can be reported in a single paragraph + table/heatmap",
      "The default threshold (cos=0.025, gap=1.0) is reasonable but not unique -- results are robust",
      "Control failure cannot be resolved by tightening thresholds -- it is structural",
      "The metric's validity concern is NOT about threshold choice but about what it measures"
    ]
  },
